 '            "Content": {\n'
 '                "Title": "Arista Networks: ANET Analyst Day: Deep Dive on AI '
 'Opportunity",\n'
 '                "Abstract": "Cloud and AI Innovators Analyst Day presented a '
 'deep dive into\\n                technology problems created by AI, and '
 'solved by Arista. As expected, financial\\n                targets laid out '
 'were largely as previewed on Q2/Q3 earnings, giving room '
 'for\\n                eventual new CFO and flexibility given customer '
 'concentration. Remain OW. Key\\n                takeaways Arista sees an '
 'incremental $5bn AI networking (back end) opportunity\\n                '
 'unfolding by 2027, part of the overall $25bn opportunity we see for '
 'cloud\\n                networkingAdvantages, and constant evolution, of EOS '
 'positions Arista to take\\n                advantage of that opportunity '
 'Enterprise / campus opportunity continues to be a\\n                '
 'meaningful growth driver10-12% growth targets for 2024 were about in-line '
 "with\\n                investor expectations, mid-teens for '22 - '27 "
 'slightly less aggressive than\\n                hoped for We attended '
 "Arista's 2023 Cloud and AI Innovators event virtually on\\n                "
 'Thursday, November 9th. AI creates networking problems, Arista '
 'developing\\n                solutions. Our move to OW recently was driven '
 'by the idea that Arista was best\\n                able to capitalize on '
 'large opportunity created by AI and the accompanying\\n                '
 "bandwidth increase both in training and utilizing LLMs. Arista's Analyst "
 'Day\\n                dove deep into the complex traffic patterns / load '
 'balancing conflicts AI\\n                traffic creates and how EOS is best '
 'able to resolve these. By resolving these\\n                problems, they '
 'see increasing ways in which Arista can participate in the '
 'AI\\n                networking opportunity ($5bn by 2027), which they '
 'classify as just the back end\\n                or training opportunity '
 'largely being served by InfiniBand today. We think this\\n                '
 '$5bn is a part of an overall $25bn cloud networking opportunity by '
 '2027,\\n                servicing not only training needs, but the increase '
 'in inference use cases and\\n                continued move of workloads to '
 'the cloud, and part of the $60bn opportunity\\n                Arista sees '
 'for itself in total (including AI, cloud, enterprise). We '
 'walked\\n                away continuing to believe in the strength of '
 "Arista's positioning. The quicker\\n                trialing / refining can "
 'be done, the sooner Arista can capitalize on AI\\n                networking '
 'opportunity. Arista laid out a $750mm 2025 target for revenue '
 'they\\n                would classify as AI networking (back end, or for use '
 'in training). This does\\n                not include revenue they may get '
 'from inference use cases, which we would\\n                classify as a '
 'bigger opportunity and one they are well positioned for. As '
 'we\\n                noted in our upgrade, Ethernet is already being trialed '
 'by META for LLaMA2\\n                clusters (META is covered by Brian '
 'Nowak). Given these trials are ongoing, we\\n                asked the '
 'company what learnings they have in early days from these trials '
 'and\\n                others, and how to turn trials into achieving the '
 '$750mm targets. They noted\\n                that with refining, both on how '
 'customers configure networks and improvements\\n                they have '
 'made to EOS, they are seeing the evidence that performance gaps '
 'to\\n                InfiniBand are closing, but it requires iterations from '
 'both parties. They also\\n                noted that trials are largely '
 'being done at 400G, where actually implementations\\n                would '
 'take place at 800G, helping further improve performance. Campus '
 '/\\n                enterprise remain meaningful opportunities, particularly '
 'as security needs grow.\\n                While most of the Analyst Event '
 'focused on the AI opportunity, the company also\\n                laid out '
 'the large enterprise opportunity they see. Much of the focus '
 "was\\n                highlighting how Arista's CloudVision common "
 'management plane simplifies and\\n                secures customer networks, '
 'helping the company gain share in data center and on\\n                '
 'campus. Adding more security elements into CloudVision, Arista announced '
 'their\\n                Zero Trust Networking Vision. Their approach is '
 'focused on leveraging the\\n                network to eliminate blindspots '
 'and silos in the network. They are partnering\\n                with '
 'Microsoft, Crowdstrike and Zscaler (newly announced) as a part of '
 'this\\n                initiative. Arista reiterated the campus goal of '
 '$750mm of campus revenue by\\n                2025, largely achieved without '
 'need of a channel, though channel investment\\n                continues. '
 'Financial outlook largely as expected, few changes to the model. '
 'The\\n                company laid out targets for 10-12% revenue growth in '
 "'24 and mid-teens growth\\n                from '22-'27 (as shown in 2). As "
 'a result, we are raising our top-line estimates\\n                for ANET '
 'in FY24, largely to account for stronger growth expectations with '
 'the\\n                Cloud Titans and Tier 2 customers. Our margins remain '
 'largely the same for FY24\\n                and FY25 top-line growth remains '
 'the same, however FY25 gross margins come down\\n                slightly '
 'due to customer mix (e.g. more cloud revenue). Net result is our '
 'new\\n                non-GAAP FY24 and FY25 revenue / EPS estimates moving '
 'up to $6,487.2mm / $7.07\\n                and $7,198.5mm / $7.55 from '
 '$6,418.3mm / $7.03 and $7,125.8mm / $7.59\\n                previously. We '
 "would note that '24 company outlook was largely in-line "
 "with\\n                investor expectations, but '22-'27 revenue growth "
 'CAGR may have been slightly\\n                short of expectations. We '
 'think given upcoming CFO transition and uncertainty in\\n                '
 '800G outcomes/timing, initial targets could eventually prove '
 'conservative.\\n                Remain OW, $220PT. While we acknowledge that '
 "Arista's current valuation is not\\n                cheap, we think it is "
 'the best exposed of our coverage universe to eventual AI\\n                '
 'networking investment, and as a result we are willing to pay a premium for '
 'the\\n                name (more in-line with software averages). In our '
 'scenario analysis, we think\\n                the earnings power of the '
 'company could reach $8.5 by 2025, making PT ~25x (or\\n                ~28x '
 'Street). This is in-line with software multiples, which has been how '
 'the\\n                company has traditionally traded. Our $220 PT is 28x '
 '25e P/E from 27x 24e P/E.\\n                Our bull case valuation is $275, '
 'or 32x a bull 25e P/E, with 32x representative\\n                of faster '
 'growing software names. Our bear case valuation is $120, with '
 '18x\\n                representing the minimum the name has traditionally '
 'traded at (on 24e earnings).\\n                Biggest risks to price target '
 'are meaningful pullback in cloud capex spend,\\n                share loss '
 'at 800G, and InfiniBand making headway as the de facto AI standard.",\n'
